You will need to initialize the palette's  with the node data with which
you wish to populate the palette.  For example, for the (simple) palette:

  <go:Palette x:Name="myPalette" NodeTemplate="..." />

you would need to perform something like the following at initialization:

  myPalette.Model.NodesSource = new String[] {
    "Alpha", "Beta", "Gamma"
  };

You also need to set AllowDrop="True" on the (s)
into which users may drop the items from the palette.

Each has an instance of this class as its property. If you want to customize the standard behavior, you can easily override any of its methods and substitute an instance of your custom layout manager class for your diagram.
public class CustomLayoutManager : LayoutManager { protected override bool CanLayoutPart(Part p, IDiagramLayout lay) { return ...; // decide dynamically which Nodes and Links should be considered for each layout } }
and install it with either XAML:
<go:Diagram ...> <go:Diagram.LayoutManager> <local:CustomLayoutManager /> </go:Diagram.LayoutManager> </go:Diagram>
or in the initialization of your Diagram control:
myDiagram.LayoutManager = new CustomLayoutManager();

member.summary:
Assigns every node in the input network to a layer.
The layering satisfies the following:
if L is a link from node U to node V,
then U.layer > V.layer;
further, U.layer - V.layer >= LinkMinLength(L).
This method can be overridden to customize how nodes are assigned layers.

member.value:
A value of zero (the default) means there is no limit;
a positive value specifies a limit.
The default value is zero.

A value of zero (the default) means there is no limit;
a positive value specifies a limit.
The default value is zero.

